      "content": "Eugenicists of the early 20th century used a variety of pseudoscientific methods and interpretations to justify racial hierarchies. They often conducted flawed intelligence tests and claimed that these tests showed inherent differences in intelligence among races. They also misused statistics and selective reporting to create the illusion of scientific validity. For example, they might compare average IQ scores among different racial groups and conclude that one group was inherently superior. They also used the concept of \"social degeneration\" to argue that certain races were more prone to criminality and immorality due to their genetic makeup. By linking race with traits like intelligence, morality, and social status, they constructed a hierarchy that placed white Europeans at the top, with other races deemed inferior. This flawed logic was used to justify discriminatory policies and practices, including forced sterilizations, immigration restrictions, and segregation. Eugenicists believed that by controlling the reproduction of certain groups, they could improve the overall genetic quality of society. This pseudoscientific approach had devastating consequences for many marginalized communities, and its influence can still be seen in some aspects of modern society.",
